UML:TaggedValue.value: All classes in this leaf have been deprecated for GeoSciML v3.0, and replaced by GeologicUnit (GeologicUnitType = ChronostratigraphicUnit), or Contact (ContactType = ChronostratigraphicBoundary, LithostratigraphicBoundary or StratigraphicBoundary)

This model allows the delivery of geochronological interpretations by describing: 1) a Specimen (eg; rock sample) 2) a related collection of sampling features within that specimen (eg; ion probe burn spots), 3) and a GeochronologicInterpretation related to that sampling collection.

The "formedDuring" association between GeologicUnit and GeochronologicEra (GeoSciML v2) is removed. Replaced by the "geologicHistory" association between GeologicUnit and GeologicEvent->GeochronologicEra.
A SamplingFeatureRelation, defined in the O&M2 package, links a StratigraphicPoint to the StratigraphicSection that hosts it
The sampledFeature association, defined in the O&M2 (Sampling Features) package, links StratigraphicSection/Point to the GeologicUnit/StratigraphicBoundary that it samples.

This model allows the delivery of geochronological interpretations by describing: 1) a Specimen (eg; rock sample) 2) a related collection of sampling features within that specimen (eg; ion probe burn spots), 3) and a GeochronologicInterpretation related to that sampling collection.
Refers to a vocabulary of terms to describe any isotopic processes relevant to the geochronological interpretation. eg:closure, isotopic mixing, Pb loss, etc
<class not required following adoption of O&M2, SWE and laboratoryAnalysis models.>>
Refers to a vocabulary of isotopic systems such as Ar-Ar, K-Ar, Nd-Sm, U-Pb, Pb-Pb, Re-Os, etc
Use a URI to name a path to a photo image of mineral grains. Use relatedSamplingFeature to relate the photo to the sampled Specimens within it. Acquisition method = 'camera'
Descriptions of the age determination acts which support this date estimate

This model allows the delivery of geochronological interpretations by describing: 1) a Specimen (eg; rock sample) 2) a related collection of sampling features within that specimen (eg; ion probe burn spots), 3) and a GeochronologicInterpretation related to that sampling collection.
Each member of the sampling collection has related OM_Observation/result(s)
Manually calculated by geochronologist based on a specific SamplingFeatureCollection (may include analyses of unknown and reference material).

Each geochronological interpretation has a mandatory association to a collection of sampling features (eg; a collection of burn spots or craters from SHRIMP analytical session).
Legacy published data for which the SamplingFeatureCollection is unknown may be delivered with SamplingFeatureCollection = 'unknown'.

An interpretation made by a geologist of the age of a specimen made by statistical analysis of a single collection of observations. A specimen may have multiple geochronological interpretations made on it, each related to a different observation collection.
Describes the isotopic system used to calculate geochronolocal age. StatisticalAgeTypes vocabulary would contain values like: Ar-Ar, K-Ar, Nd-Sm, Pb-Pb, Rb-Sr, Re-Os, U-Pb, etc
Use GeoSciML GeologicEvent to describe event age, process and environment. e.g, Event age = 350 Ma +/- 3 Ma. Event process = intrusion, extrusion, metamorphism. Event environment = plutonic, marine.
Describes any isotopic events that are relevant to the interpretation. eg; closure, isotopic mixing, Pb loss, etc
Indicates whether this interpretation is the preferred interpretation (ie; the analytical data may be reinterpreted)
Use ISO metadata citation element to describe author and other reference information. Can be used to describe reference for new or legacy data
A SamplingFeatureRelation may be used to associate a Specimen with a StratigraphicPoint
Refers to a vocabulary of isotopic systems such as Ar-Ar, K-Ar, Nd-Sm, U-Pb, Pb-Pb, Re-Os, etc
<class not required following adoption of O&M2, SWE and laboratoryAnalysis models.>>
Refers to a vocabulary of terms to describe any isotopic processes relevant to the geochronological interpretation. eg:closure, isotopic mixing, Pb loss, etc
Need a constraint to limit the prototype association from GeologicEvent to StratigraphicPoint to be allowed only with an appropriate eventProcess (eg: deposition, eruption, crystallisation)
Several StratigraphicPoints may be associated with a boundary, but only one may have GSSP ratified status. The others are proposed equivalent.
Association is suppressed for GSSP purposes

All classes in this leaf have been deprecated for GeoSciML v3.0, and replaced by GeologicUnit (GeologicUnitType = ChronostratigraphicUnit), or Contact (ContactType = ChronostratigraphicBoundary, LithostratigraphicBoundary or StratigraphicBoundary)
Used for pre-Ediacaran and Pleistocene / Holocene boundaries in the standard timescale

The association of an era with a stratotype is optional. In the GSSP approach recommended by ICS for the Global Geologic Timescale, Unit Stratotypes are not used. Rather, the association of an Era with geologic units and sections is indirect, via the association of an era with Boundaries, which are in turn tied to Stratotype Points, which occur within host Stratotype Sections. Note that the "German School" defines stratigraphic eras conceptually, without reference to stratotypes.

The classic "Geologic Timescale" comprising an ordered, hierarchical set of named "eras" is an example of an Ordinal Temporal Reference System. It may be calibrated with reference to a numeric Temporal Coordinate System, but is in principle defined independently.
The set of all strata on earth that were formed during the related Era. Replaced by GeologicUnit (GeologicUnitType = ChronstratigraphicUnit)

Event is most often biostratigraphic, e.g. "First appearance of conodont X", but sometimes a paleomagnetic reversal, a chemostratigraphic, cyclostratigraphic or astrochronological event. It is a description of an event hypothsized to be demonstrated at the GSSP Point (Golden Spike). Note that since the Point is the ultimate reference object, the *Event*, rather than the *Point*, must be changed if evidence related to the original "event" is found on the wrong side of the Point. This constrast with an"event-chronologic" approach, by which the event would be defined first, so the position of the Point would have to be adjusted as a consequence of new evidence.
Replaced by RankTerm vocabulary on GeologicUnit (where GeologicUnitType = ChronostratigraphicUnit)
Classes with this colour are required to represent the GSSP model This cross-section of the model must be implemented
Objects from the classes within this boundary have a physical realisation, even if it may not be fully known.
The set of all strata on earth that were formed during the related Era
